{"key":"post-12944444","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12944444</id>\n<content>I wouldn't flatten it out too much because drying becomes a concern.&amp;nbsp; Not all sclerotia producing species only form stones at the edges.&amp;nbsp; Some produce stones all the way through.&amp;nbsp; It should be done in six to eight weeks if you use weak liquid coffee to hydrate the rye berries.&amp;nbsp; Leaving the bags longer than that can often lead to the sclerotia going rancid.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I show a method of preparing filter patch bags in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Sawdust-Woodchips&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;sawdust/woodchips&lt;/a&gt; chapter of the video where you slip a tyvek sleeve into the bag before sterilizing.&amp;nbsp; This allows steam to vent, but prevents contaminants entering the bag as it cools.&amp;nbsp; This is the method we use on our mushroom farm, and often leave the bags unsealed this way for over a week before inoculation without problems.&amp;nbsp; After inoculation, you can seal the bag with electrical twist ties, or steel tie wire, etc.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12945319</next>\n<prev>12944311</prev>\n<first>12944293</first>\n<last>12945319</last>\n<when>1279978908</when>\n<utime>07/24/10 04:41 PM</utime>\n</post>"}